This is independent of this PR, but as I saw it now, this check should probably go something like this instead:
```python
arr = spec(shape)
try:
    arr = floatX(arr)
except Exception:
    ... did not return an array-like ...
if arr.shape != shape:
    ... did not return correct shape ...
return theano.shared(arr, name=name)
```
This should also handle scalars correctly.

Ahh, I see what's happening.  The way this is written, it's trying to populate that list before we have any data in the ``resultset_store``.  But we don't need that list before we have any resultsets loaded.  So it's just a matter of doing this call a the wrong time.

I also think we should be doing this in ``ui/plugins/controller.js`` instead of ``pinboard.js``.

If you remove your changes from ``pinboard.js`` and add/update this code in ``controller.js`` it should work:

        $scope.$watch('getCountPinnedJobs()', function(newVal, oldVal) {
            if (oldVal === 0 && newVal > 0) {
                $scope.isPinboardVisible = true;
                getRevisionTips($scope.repoName, $scope.originalTipList);
            }
        });

        $scope.originalTipList = [];
        var getRevisionTips = function(projectName, list) {
            list.splice(0, list.length);
            var rsArr = ThResultSetStore.getResultSetsArray(projectName);
            _.forEach(rsArr, rs => {
                list.push({
                    revision: rs.revision,
                    author: rs.author
                });
            });
        };

Note, you're updating the ``viewJob`` function that's already there.  Since that's where the pinboard is shown.

Would you mind playing with this and see how it goes?  Thanks!  :)

@carver do want to accommodate  (optional) encoder/decoder hooks ?
```python
def json_encoder(obj, CustomEncoder=None):
    try:
        encode = json.dumps(obj, cls=CustomEncoder)
         ...
# and
def json_decoder(json_string, obj_hook=None):
    try:
        decode = json.loads(json_string, object_hook=obj_hook)
        ...
```

It would be better not to make this a str/unicode subclass in the first place, if it's just wrapping some str or unicode object then there's no copying involved, just the allocation of this "tag". It also should greatly simplify the code. Something as simple as this would suffice:

```python
class RawJSON(object):
    def __init__(self, encoded_json):
        self.encoded_json = encoded_json
```

> Callback connectionCb
> Callback messageCb

These callbacks are low-level c callbacks that use low-level ids, handles and error codes as params. It would be nice to hide this details from library user. I suggest using observer-like approach. We can define one interface 

```
interface ConnectionObserver {
  void onConnection(AgentConnection connection);
  void onMessage(AgentConnection connection, String message);
}
```

And ask a user to pass implementation of this observer as the latest parameter of agentConnect. This parameter will replace both callbacks.

